Local Engagement as a Countermeasure against Populism
PARIS – The parties that once dominated the Western democracies have been shaken at their core.
Many – including in France, Italy, Greece, and the United Kingdom – have suffered resounding electoral defeats.
Others have changed so drastically that only the name remains.
The Republican Party of US President Donald Trump has little in common with that of the former president Ronald Reagan.
These developments resemble each other everywhere in the West.
The leaders of once dominant parties oscillate between denial and despair, while populists fish out their traditional supporters.
Some refuse to acknowledge a legitimate reason for their defeat and dismiss their opponents' supporters as "pitiable," as Hillary Clinton did shortly before she lost to Trump in 2016; others are too frightened by the populist tide to launch a counteroffensive.
Yet neither denial nor self-satisfaction will resolve the entrenched political situation.
The Progressives must reposition themselves, and this begins with diagnosing the shortcomings of traditional parties.
Part of the problem is that the traditional parties have not recognized the real issues of our time.
Still trapped on the old ideological battlefields, they ignored the declining social mobility, the worsening environmental crises, the increasing geographic inequality, tensions regarding multiculturalism, and other issues that actually matter to voters.
Decades ago, they were the avant-garde.
Today they are all alone in the forest and wonder where everyone has gone.
The social sciences might have an answer as to why the mainstream has strayed from the path.
The gap between their objective analysis of reality and the policies of governments has widened into a chasm.
In most Western countries, economists have long been aware of the growing disparity in income and other indicators between some affluent cities benefiting from globalization and the rest of the country.
Yet before the government of French President Emmanuel Macron did so, no national prime minister had implemented tax cuts based on residence.
As a result of this policy, 1% of France's GDP is now being redistributed primarily to the poorest parts of the country.
In addition, the traditional parties could learn something by listening directly to the voters instead of only through the filters of the media and opinion institutes.
In 2016, Macron's movement En Marche! launched the largest door-to-door survey in French history.
What the voters told the questioners then became the basis of Macron's presidential campaign.
For example, "La Grande Marche" had collected countless statements from women about harassment more than a year before the revelations about Harvey Weinstein's alleged sexual misconduct toward women, and Macron promised to address the issue if he were elected.
At that time, Macron's stance made him a target of jokes by his opponents; however, with the emergence of the #MeToo era, the laughter quickly faded.
However, a precise understanding of society alone is not sufficient.
The traditional parties also suffer from poor organization.
You long believed that modern politics should be organized around elections, where activists distribute flyers at intervals and cheer on the candidates.
That was less cynicism than a symptom of an approach that views democracy as a marketplace consisting of state providers (the government) and consumers (the citizens).
According to this view, the sole purpose of a party is to seize and maintain power.
It's no wonder that citizens, and even party members, feel ignored between elections.
Despite these weaknesses, the established parties had a number of advantages that delayed their collapse.
In recent years, they had a technological advantage over less established opponents, and they were the only political actors with organized voter groups capable of mobilizing people to vote, organizing protests, and launching petitions.
But this model no longer fits.
Today, citizens refuse to be mere consumers of state policy.
Along with a higher level of education came new demands for participation.
The voters want to be treated as political actors with their own rights, and not as pawns in the chess game of others.
Moreover, governments themselves are no longer the only providers of political measures.
That is one of the hard lessons we had to learn during the two years we worked alongside Macron in the Élysée Palace.
The most important political challenges today – climate change, religious extremism, digital upheavals, and gender equality – cannot be solved by national governments alone.
These challenges require profound cultural changes and, in most cases, measures at subnational and supranational levels.
And finally, technology has lowered the barriers to political participation, meaning that traditional parties can no longer rely on the incumbent advantage and established support networks.
Whoever can handle Google, Twitter, and Facebook well does not need a century-old party apparatus.
Political movements must be reorganized accordingly.
The focus should be on concrete measures and not just on elections.
The formal administrative structure of a party should serve as an administrative "back office"; the front office should be staffed by people on the ground.
At La République En Marche!, we refer to these as local civic projects.
These can range from after-school reading courses and integration programs for immigrants to cooperative vegetable gardens and digital training for seniors.
In any case, it is about offering solutions tailored to local problems in order to strengthen the communities in this way.
Such projects should today be considered indispensable complements to state policy.
In the future, a party's ability to offer rewarding avenues for political and community engagement will be crucial to its attractiveness.
And by daily demonstrating their reform policies "live," the parties have already laid the groundwork for success on election day.
If voters refuse to listen to what one has to say, the answer is not to shout louder.
This is the harsh lesson that the traditional parties have learned.
Only those who demonstrate a commitment to improving people's lives, rather than simply winning elections, can win people over to their side.
Restoring the connection to the concerns of voters therefore goes hand in hand with adapting the party organizations.
To offer a successful alternative to populism, we need progressive politics at the local level.
